### Throttle: fires at most once per 200ms
```js
function throttle(fn, limit) {
  let lastCall = 0;
  return function(...args) {
    const now = Date.now();
    if (now - lastCall >= limit) {
      lastCall = now;
      return fn.apply(this, args);
    }
  };
}
window.addEventListener('scroll', throttle(onScroll, 200));
```
Throttle = rate limiting. Debounce = waiting for silence.

### React lazy route loading
```jsx
import { lazy, Suspense } from 'react';

const Dashboard = lazy(() => import('./Dashboard'));

function App() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<Spinner />}>
      <Dashboard />
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```
The Dashboard bundle is only downloaded when the user navigates to it.

### Impure function (unpredictable)
```js
let tax = 0.2;
function getPrice(base) {
  return base + base * tax; // Depends on external state!
}
```
### Pure function (predictable)
```js
function getPrice(base, taxRate) {
  return base + base * taxRate; // Same input = same output
}
```
Pure functions are the foundation of reliable, testable code.

### JavaScript: bug at runtime
```js
function add(a, b) { return a + b; }
add('5', 3); // Returns '53' not 8 — silent bug!
```
### TypeScript: bug at compile time
```ts
function add(a: number, b: number): number {
  return a + b;
}
add('5', 3);
// Error: Argument of type 'string' is not assignable to 'number'
```
The compiler is your first line of testing.

### Tightly coupled (hard to test)
```js
function sendEmail(to, msg) {
  const mailer = new ProductionMailer(); // Hardcoded!
  mailer.send(to, msg);
}
```
### Dependency injection (easy to test)
```js
function sendEmail(to, msg, mailer) {
  mailer.send(to, msg);
}
// In tests:
sendEmail('a@b.com', 'hello', new MockMailer());
// In production:
sendEmail('a@b.com', 'hello', new ProductionMailer());
```
